-HAFFvsDCr4.transcription: This is an artwork from South Korea called the Round Table. It consists of 18 headless mechanical figures made of straw, each trying to claim a single head rolling on top, while balancing a table on their backs. Whenever one of the figures lifts itself up to try to claim the head, the table tilts, causing the head to roll further away, ensuring the struggle continues. While the figures endlessly suffer, three large blackbirds circle above, representing the upper class watching the struggles of the working class below

ragJEXeqcbE.transcription: These are three optical illusions that use perspective. This first one is known as the Penrose Triangle. It's an optical illusion of an object which can be depicted in a perspective drawing, but apparently can't exist as a solid object. This next illusion is an Escher cube, sort of not really an impossible object. I suppose you could make a cube any old way, but this one behaves a little bizarrely, and that's because it's not a cube at all. This last one tricks your brain into thinking you're seeing a convex 3D item, an object that behaves sort of counterintuitively when you move it, but in reality, it's a concave 3D object, and with the light, your brain tries to figure out a solution for what it's seeing. lfitOyblkDQ.transcription: This girl is a real genius. Here are some fun science experiments you can try at home. Make a circle of steel wool and place a cell phone inside. When you dial the phone, the steel wool will spark, showing the radiation from the call. Touch garlic with your hand and you can easily lift an egg yolk due to the disulfide bond. Draw a circle with garlic in a pan and your eggs will cook round. Sprinkle salt on a table and you can stand an egg on it. Fold five toothpicks in half, place them together and add water to the center. The toothpicks will form a star due to water tension. Normally you can't poke a straw through a potato, but if you seal the tip with your thumb, you can easily break through the potato with compressed air. Pour Sprite on a wilted rose and it will come back to life. Shake sand in a pie pan and add a small magnetic ball and it will draw patterns on the sand. To simulate a rocket launch, break a match, roll it in tin foil and ignite it. Follow for more life hack tips

Evie7TV-E8s.transcription: Why is it the tightrope walkers are always carrying a long pole? Well, you fall when your center of mass, basically your body's balance point, goes outside the base of support or your feet. At that point, there's nothing to support you against the pole of gravity, and you topple over. But if you add a pole with weights on each end, look what happens. Adding the weights pulls your cumulative center of mass below your support base. So toppling over now requires it to move up. Gravity is now your friend. It constantly pulls the center of mass back down to stabilize things out. It's the same thing with these balancing bird toys. The wings are weighted, so the center of mass is actually below its balancing point at the beak. Although holding the pole low does lower their center of mass, they don't use huge weights, and that's because the biggest benefit of the pole comes from the link. These two rods weigh the same, but when I spin them with the same force, the shorter one rotates way faster than the longer one. That's because the longer one has more rotational inertia, meaning it's harder to rotate. So if you hold a long pull, that actually makes you harder to rotate as well. And you actually know this, which is why when you're trying to balance, you automatically put your arms out. But there's another trick to stay on a tightrope that doesn't require a pull at all. And it's actually one of the really fun Crunch Labs toys that gets delivered right to your porch, where you build it yourself as I teach you all the juicy physics that make them work.
